Fukushima and the collapse of derivatives.
CAMBRIDGE – Financial commentators have likened the Japanese earthquake, tsunami, and nuclear catastrophe to the role of derivatives in the 2008 financial crisis.
The resemblance is quite clear: each of these activities generates huge profits and includes a very low but explosive risk.
Despite the similarity between the two types of crisis ending there, it is where the way to prevent their recurrence begins.
In the case of the Fukushima nuclear power plant, a once-in-a-century flood, combined with defects in design that are usually harmless, caused a shutdown of the cooling water circulation in the reactors and significant radiation leaks.
In the case of financial markets, an unanticipated collapse of property values, combined with defects in design in the markets for derivatives and repos, has impaired the ability of major financial institutions to meet their debt obligations.
Although the underlying risks originated outside the systems – a tsunami for Fukushima, over-investment in mortgage loans for financial institutions – design flaws and bad luck ensured that the systems were unable to contain the damage.
In the United States, AIG, Bear Stearns, and Lehman Brothers – all with significant investments in derivatives and/or repos – went bankrupt, causing a freeze in credit markets for several long weeks.
We now understand fairly well the risks and design flaws of Fukushima.
We cannot say the same about the risks of derivatives that shook the global economy.
At Fukushima, the teams of workers valiantly attempt to stop the radiation leaks.
However, the efforts to address similar risks in derivatives are misguided and will not enable us to avoid the next financial crisis.
We are recreating similar derivatives and financial structures, on top of the same active errors.
Financial actors use financial products to transfer risk: for instance, one actor takes on the risk of euro fluctuations but not the risk on the yen, while for another, it is the opposite.
In this case, the first one promises to deliver euros by June 1st, and the second one promises to deliver yen.
If a currency loses value relative to another, the loser pays the difference.
Repo transactions are financial transactions.
Financial institutions sell assets, such as Treasury bonds or mortgage-backed securities, for cash and promise to repurchase these assets subsequently, typically the following day, hence the name "repo", which is an abbreviation for the English verb repurchase, or to buy back.
The problem is that the short-term cash from these repos accounts for a large portion of the balance sheets of the largest financial institutions, implying that even minor financial shocks can significantly affect them.
Certain institutions can then become cut off from repo financing, as in 2008, and go bankrupt, as did Bear Stearns.
Taken individually, repo or derivatives transactions are hardly blameworthy.
Each individually transfers risk in a legitimate manner to those better equipped to bear it, or enables financial participation.
However, when excessively used by systemically vital institutions, they can blow up the financial system, due to its design flaws.
Even today, roughly 70% of the liabilities of major US financial institutions are comprised of very short-term loans, such as repos due the following day.
In the United States, the primary design flaws are found in bankruptcy legislation, which largely exempts derivatives and repos from most standard constraints in the event of bankruptcy.
For example, investors holding derivative contracts or repos with financially fragile institutions can seize the company's assets before - and to the detriment of - its normal creditors. In doing so, they can decide its fate, whereas, with a bit more time, the company in question might have been able to survive.
Such actions ruined AIG, Bear Stearns, and others during the financial crisis.
Worse still, because derivatives investors and repo holders end up at the front of the repayment queue in so many ways, they have fewer incentives to encourage market discipline by closely checking the solvency of their counterparties and carefully rationing their exposure to any single counterparty.
Typically, they will be repaid anyway.
Someone has to be first.
Other financial actors must bear more risk because the exemptions of derivatives and repo actors place them at the forefront in case of bankruptcy.
Normally, one would expect others to have a greater interest in encouraging more market discipline.
However, the government is often the next in line, as the guarantor of "too-big-to-fail" financial institutions, and, in any case, it is ill-equipped to regulate these markets on a daily basis.
It is not financially agile; it often confines itself to the regulated market; and when economic conditions are good, no official wants to spoil the party.
The US Congress had an opportunity to address this flaw in the major overhaul of finance it adopted last summer through the Dodd Frank bill.
However, it did not seize the opportunity.
If derivatives investors, repo holders, and credit-default swap investors did not enjoy preferential treatment, they would behave differently.
First and foremost, they would insist more often that their counterparties be adequately capitalized.
They accepted the risk generated by ultra-low capitalizations when it was essentially government American money at stake; they would be less inclined to do so if it were their own money on the line.
The public perceives risks of the Fukushima type differently from risks associated with derivatives.
Many people fear the nuclear risks, which are striking, triggering a slowdown in the sector that must face security concerns.
But the markets for derivatives and repos present risks that are poorly understood, difficult to communicate in the media, and complicated to debate and resolve for politicians.
During a crisis, these markets attract public attention and scorn, but when the economy stabilizes again, ordinary people lose all interest, leaving the financial sector to control its own destiny with the legislative body.
Concerning risks of the Fukushima type, analysts are already discussing how nuclear power plants can be designed and built to contain earthquake and tsunami-related risks through passive cooling systems.
Today, it is considered possible to design nuclear power plants that can keep their fuel rods cool even in the event of a complete loss of electrical power.
However, little significant progress has been made so far to prevent the damage that prioritizing derivatives and repo holders in case of bankruptcy could cause during a new financial system crisis.
New rules are being developed, requiring end-users (such as oil companies using derivatives to hedge against unexpected changes in oil prices) and others to post high-quality collateral.
However, these rules do not address the main issue: the weak incentives for market discipline for the main financial institutions.
It seems like we're trying to address the root causes of the Fukushima disaster, but we're only treating the symptoms by tightening regulations on the oil industry, much like we're only addressing the financial crisis by implementing new rules on derivatives.
We should examine how to fully make investors in derivatives and repos bear the risk associated with their decisions when they conduct transactions with systemically vital financial institutions.
Instead, we survived the 2008 financial tsunami only to rebuild at the same location, with the same financial flaws and the same defective design.
